g to work, eight kilometers to work, and eight kilometers back from work. The work lasted ten hours. The work lasted ten hours. The work went on under a speed-up. They were driving [us] with clubs; with sticks we were hurried at work. There we got to eat four hundred grams of bread, twenty grams margarine, and a bit . . . a liter of soup, which was spinach, what they called it. Spinach leafs which were covered [?] with sand."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "904.748","u": "What was the name of the lager?"},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "906.517","u": "The lager was called Blechhammer."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "909.372","u": "Oh. And the Works were . . . ?"},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "911.364","u": "The Works were Upper-Silesian Hydraulic Works, they belonged to the government."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "915.559","u": "Hm . . ."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "915.861","u": "There were also the Herman Goehring Works."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "918.245","u": "Well . . ."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "921.927","u": "From there, after spending there seven weeks, I went over to a second lager. It was called [name not clear&#226;Laue . . . ] and the conditions were still worse. That was in Upper Silesia. In Polish Upper Silesia. There we were under very hard conditions. Very bad food. Ordinarily [?] we were getting only two hundred grams of bread, and twenty grams butter and half a liter of soup."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "949.338","u": "The butter was naturally . . . What . . . ?"},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "951.028","u": "No, that was margarine butter, in a concentration camp there was no talk about real butter. That time it was not yet a concentration camp, it was a lager for compulsory labor. There at work I had an accident. I was hurt by a rusty bolt, that is a wheel with rusty teeth hurt my leg, and I got blood poisoning. In spite of that I was compelled . . . I suffered for six weeks. And my comrades took me to work [leading me] under my arms. And to work I had to go. If not, there was a place, and one was sent away to the famous lager Kozel."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "989.370","u": "Hm . . ."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "990.608","u": "Kozel too is in Upper Silesia, German Upper Silesia. There too, many transports were burned."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "998.352","u": "In Kozel . . ."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "999.137","u": "Kozel . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "999.862","u": "That is not in Auschwitz."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1000.786","u": "No, Kozel."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1001.860","u": "Aha . . ."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1002.494","u": "There were many lagers besides the famous lagers, which, so to speak were smaller."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1007.233","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1007.432","u": "But they did not lag behind in their horrors."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1011.356","u": "Well, what did they have there? Crematories, or . . ."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1013.728","u": "Yes, a crematory . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1015.750","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1015.992","u": "Burned . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1016.885","u": "What? Were they first . . . or what?"},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1019.632","u": "First they were gassed."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1020.948","u": "[Word not clear]"},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1021.389","u": "&#39;Everything&#39; was gassed."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1022.584","u": "Yes . . . Nu . . ."},    {"who": "Jacob Schwarzfitter", "start": "1023.822","u": "From there, from that lager, I was transferred again to a second lager, [two